text: I love Oliver Stone (and Nicolas Cage!) and want to see this, but my goodness is this trailer shittily cut with corny reaction shots stitched together. When will trailers stop doing cheap imitations of emotion and just show a story to get people interested in seeing a movie? Hearing screeching noises along with a phone ringing and dramatic cuts between unrelated shots is not dramatic. We have nothing invested in this crappily cut trailer. We're not wondering, "Oh my goodness, who's on the other end of that phone?!" Because it's a fucking hastily cut trailer that has absolutely no build up to that moment or anything else. It's not shocking. Fuck off.

text: "Most Americans don't want freedom, they want security"  This reminded me of a quote from Alexander McCandless in Into The Wild <3  ‚Äúmake a radical change in your lifestyle and begin to boldly do things which you may previously never have thought of doing, or been too hesitant to attempt. So many people live within unhappy circumstances and yet will not take the initiative to change their situation because they are conditioned to a life of security, conformity, and conservation, all of which may appear to give one peace of mind, but in reality nothing is more damaging to the adventurous spirit within a man than a secure future. The very basic core of a man's living spirit is his passion for adventure. The joy of life comes from our encounters with new experiences, and hence there is no greater joy than to have an endlessly changing horizon, for each day to have a new and different sun. If you want to get more out of life, you must lose your inclination for monotonous security and adopt a helter-skelter style of life that will at first appear to you to be crazy. But once you become accustomed to such a life you will see its full meaning and its incredible beauty.‚Äù

text: FINALLY someone made a big(ger) budget movie with at least recognizable actors and enough mindless Hollywood window dressings to potentially capture the attention of an otherwise rather willfully ignorant American populace. I wrote a book inspired by this nightmare this awhile back because you can't imagine a scarier enemy than one who is omniscient and omnipotent; and omniscience and omnipotence is certainly the end game of the New World Order George HW Bush talked about on September 11, 1991. His full speech is here on Youtube, if you're curious.  If you want a more realistic portrayal of the truth, and a very horrifying movie experience, watch CitizenFour, available on iTunes, it is excellent and probably less biased than any film by Oliver Stone, although I greatly applaud what he's doing. Trying to get people to comprehend the massive behemoth they're funding with their own tax dollars as their cities rot and their educated get crippled by massive loan debt is an uphill battle, and most simply can't handle factual documentaries.   Most people also do not connect the dots between the things Snowden warned of, the never-ending war on terror that grants perpetual wartime powers to the government, and the FBI's current battle to cripple encryption. You would think people would care, given that they're paying for all of it, and that even if they trust a group of faceless "protectors" (or just bored pervs) with access to their every digital conversation, and real life conversation within range of an internet connected microphone (every phone and laptop these days), there may come a day when these people are replaced by new people who are not as trustworthy. This is why you never grant absolute, unquestioned powers to a governing body. Would you trust a drone capable of killing you hovering outside your house, controlled by a police officer who could see inside your home, internet connection, and hear your every conversation every second of every day? It's not there today, but anyone with an imagination and even the most casual awareness of what's happening on the news can see how the police force will be evolving from body cams in the future.   One must also consider the fact that the American government's sloppy war on terror is at least partially to blame for some of the problems we now face in the form of ISIS. Before you tear my head off, do a little unbiased research. I fully support American troops, and find them incredibly brave. I also love America enough to get angry when I see its Constitution getting shredded before my eyes. One can support America without supporting a rushed, sloppy war on terror or the government who used the fear associated with 9/11 to start it. There are also some sources claiming people within our government past and present FUND terrorists simply to get rich and maintain power...which is pretty much the job description of any career politician who does not believe in limited government and the separation of government from the free market, is it not? Google "libertarianism" if you don't understand what I mean by "limited government".   Did you know the F-35 military program yielded next to no benefit to everyday Americans and yet could have funded all of their college educations for 20 years according to Mike Gilmore, a Pentagon weapons tester? Think about that the next time you consider college tuition cost. We're funding people to play with war toys and spy toys and are okay with it at the cost of our economy, world standing, education, and childrens' futures.   The debate over Snowden is simply a debate over the need for checks and balances in all branches of power and an informed populace who can influence their government without merely submitting ignorantly to whatever the government chooses to do, now and in the future; shadow governments with never-ending wartime powers are under no one's control but their own whims. And if you trust humankind enough to grant a group of humans absolute power, then I would suggest you are massively ignorant of both human nature, and all of human history. But most people cannot even begin to desire to imagine such a horrific worldview, lest their brains explode. Major motion pictures watered down with Hollywood drama and just enough sprinkling of facts like this, even if a bit cheesy compared to much richer documentaries on the subject, are certainly a step in the right direction, so I don't understand the hatred in the comments about this being a glossy Hollywood movie.   If only they would make a movie stating the obvious, that two planes do not cause three buildings to implode (google "World Trade Center 7" if you don't recall the building that mysteriously imploded across the street, even when towers 5 and 6 stood after being pummeled by exponentially more debris), nor would a plane be able to fly fast enough or low enough to vaporize against the Pentagon; maybe then people would really wake up and question the role of their current ruling class. Dynasties are not the answer. Trump is not the answer. Socialism is not the answer. What America was founded upon is the answer, and what the war on terror is really a war against the founding principles of America. America government was designed to have checks and balances. The public was meant to be informed, and elect those who represented them, not billionaires or dictators. Perhaps the general public should educate themselves with the ideas behind the Constitution. And, Google "Gary Johnson" while you're at it, if you're feeling more awake after reading this.

text: apparently JFK is in the description  Academy Award¬Æ-winning director Oliver Stone, who brought Platoon, Born on the Fourth of July, Wall Street and JFK to the big screen, tackles the most important and fascinating true story of the 21st century. Snowden, the politically-charged, pulse-pounding thriller starring Joseph Gordon-Levitt and Shailene Woodley, reveals the incredible untold personal story of Edward Snowden, the polarizing figure who exposed shocking illegal surveillance activities by the NSA and became one of the most wanted men in the world. text: The sad thing is that I assumed the government was basically spying on the American public well before Snowden. When his name became well-known, I wasn't surprised at all. In fact, my first thought was "why is this news, don't people already know this?" I assumed anything you put online is basically as good as public. I lost most trust in the government a long time ago. Though I don't believe they were involved in things like the 9-11 attacks,¬†as some conspiracy theorists claim, I wouldn't be surprised to find out that they were involved. The government has vastly overstepped its legitimate bounds. Even with those few roles that I would consider legitimate government (law enforcement, judicial system, and¬†military), these things have no escaped corruption and abuse. I have no problem with security, but I would never want that over privacy. "Those who would give up essential Liberty, to purchase a little temporary Safety, deserve neither Liberty nor Safety" (Benjamin Franklin).

text: As a response to someone who was asking why we should care about the invasions of privacy set in place by our intelligence agencies (which discussion he promptly deleted):   "If you think privacy is unimportant for you because you have nothing to hide, you might as well say free speech is unimportant for you because you have nothing to say. " Nobody should ever need to justify why they "need" a right, the burden of justification falls on the one trying to tear that right away.And even if they did, you can't give away the rights of the people right because you think that "having nothing to hide" is a reason not to have it.  The right to privacy is the tight to self. You decide what to share about you, and what not to share about you. As long as there have been windows, there have been curtains. Privacy is a part of basic human nature, and most reasonable people are grateful for the fact that we've been provided with the tools to keep said privacy secured. By your logic, you wouldn't give a damn if I broke into your computer, phone, or home because you have "nothing to hide" from me anyway. In truth, it doesn't fucking matter, because your property is YOUR property, not someone else's to go through.  Not to mention the fact that the NSA themselves admitted to twelve specific instances of employees "misusing" their surveillance programs (https://www.nsa.gov/public_info/press_room/2013/grassley_letter.pdf). I don't quite believe that you wouldn't give a damn if someone broke into something containing your personal information and shared it with others or some such related thing.   Also, historically, intelligence programs have COMPLETELY violated protocol, causing mass disruption in multiple LAWFUL CONGREGATIONS OF CIVILIANS, including Civil Rights movements (e.g Martin Luther King Jr.), anti-war and violence activists, Puerto Rican Independence groups, and others. COINTELPRO is one of the most well known intelligence agencies for this. FBI director Edgar Hoover literally ISSUED these directives, causing disruption in civilian lives, using tactics that "included anonymous phone calls, IRS audits, and the creation of documents that would divide [them] internally."   Hope that helps you "understand why we should care."

text: ...to save it (his country)?  What a load of complete bullshit that is!  If you have a security clearance of any kind, you sign an NDA, or Non-Disclosure Agreement.  It is part of your contract with whatever organization you sign up for (armed forces, CIA, NSA, etc.).  It says that you will not in any form release classified material to the public.  It also states the punishments for doing so.  If you sign it, then you are bound to it just like anything else you sign in a contractual agreement.  This is fact, this is reality.  What he did is just like giving away your football teams play book to opposing football teams.  When enemies find out how we do things, they have the upper hand.  Given enough info, we not only lose battles, but wars.  Knowing the enigma code in WW2 was a major factor to our victory over Germany.  Alan Turing, who made that possible, was a cryptologist, the same thing Snowden was.  When he told the public what he did, he let the world know.  All it would take is one terrorist changing how he operates based on Snowden's info.  When enemies change tactics, it can often take a long time to gather any more information about him.  Information like what he is doing and when.  So, then attacks happen because we weren't able to get the info necessary to stop the attack in time.  We live in a strange time as our freedoms pose us a major risk too.  I'm not sure how you can secure everyone here and NOT monitor cell phones and internet.  Most of what he says is probably BS.  Think of how many emails, text messages, and cell p hone calls go on each day.  There is no way in hell that any organization could hire enough people to monitor all of them in real time.  So this is just another case of something blown out of proportion like US citizens ALWAYS do!

text: Totally looking forward to the amount of inaccuracies this film will spout about section 702 & 215. For a detailed, accurate understanding the following citations do very well at dispelling such common myths. 'In Defense of FAA Section 702: An examination of its justification, operational employment and legal underpinnings' http://www.hoover.org/sites/default/files/research/docs/indefenseoffaasection702_inglis-kosseff.pdf "If NSA employees fail to follow any of the detailed limitations on their ability to collect or use the Section 702 data, they are subject to a number of internal compliance positions, including the employees‚Äô supervisors, NSA‚Äôs director of civil liberties and privacy, NSA‚Äôs general counsel, and NSA‚Äôs inspector general. And while concerns about potential abuse properly inform the diligence with which controls are designed and enforced, numerous and extensive investigations conducted by outside parties before and after the sensational claims of Edward Snowden in 2013 have yet  to document a single case of abuse of Section 702 data by an individual or a systemic abuse by the NSA. Indeed, as Geoffrey Stone, the Edward H. Levi Distinguished Service Professor of Law at the University of Chicago and a member of the President‚Äôs 2013 NSA Review Group, stated in an op-ed in March 2014: _From the outset, I approached my responsibilities as a member of the Review Group with great skepticism about the NSA. I am a long-time civil libertarian, a member of the National Advisory Council of the ACLU, and a former Chair of the Board of the American Constitution Society._ _To say I was skeptical about the NSA is, in truth, an understatement. I came away from my work on the Review Group with a view of the NSA that I found quite surprising._  _Not only did I find that the NSA had helped to thwart numerous terrorist plots against the United States and its allies in the years since 9/11, but I also_ _found that it is an organization that operates with a high degree of integrity and a deep commitment to the rule of law._ _Like any organization dealing with extremely complex issues, the NSA on_ _occasion made mistakes in the implementation of its authorities, but it invariably reported those mistakes upon discovering them and worked conscientiously to correct its errors._ _The Review Group found no evidence that the NSA had knowingly or intentionally engaged in unlawful or unauthorized activity. To the contrary, it has put in place carefully-crafted internal procedures to ensure that it operates within the bounds of its lawful authority."_  And the conclusion: *A complete examination of Section 702 reveals a program that is painstakingly designed* *to protect the privacy of US persons to the greatest extent possible while also* *gathering valuable intelligence for national security.* *Section 702 achieves the twin goals of the Constitution‚Äôs* *preamble: providing for the common defense and securing the blessings of liberty.* And as noted in an extensive 2013 analysis, the United States is the only nation in the world where ‚Äú. . . _such surveillance is subject to review by courts presided over by_ _federal judges,_  _with appeals possible to the US Supreme Court._ _The law enforcement agencies tasked with complying with FISA_ _are required to provide regular compliance reports to the_ _Congressional committees with responsibility over national security.‚Äù_ Given the Constitution‚Äôs mandate for limited but effective government, this burden is both appropriate and well imposed. It remains the gold standard in a world searching for the means to achieve the dual aims of security and the defense of individual liberties. *The critics of Section 702 have failed to provide persuasive evidence that Section 702 is either unconstitutional* *or bad public policy, and therefore have not made the case for modification or repeal of the law. For that reason, Congress should* *reauthorize Section 702 without any significant amendments."  Privacy and Civil Liberties Oversight Board: Report on the Surveillance Program Operated Pursuant to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act' https://www.pclob.gov/library/702-Report.pdf (page 50):  'Minimization and Related Requirements: What Are the Limitations Regarding How the Data is Acquired, Who May View It, How Long It Is Retained, and with Whom It May be Shared?' "Section 702 requires that all acquired data be subject to ‚Äúminimization procedures.‚Äù210 Minimization procedures are best understood as a set of controls on data to balance privacy and national security interests. Specifically, under FISA, minimization procedures must be ‚Äúspecific procedures . . . that are reasonably designed in light of the purpose and technique of the particular surveillance to minimize the acquisition and retention, and prohibit the dissemination, of nonpublicly available information concerning unconsenting United States persons consistent with the need of theUnited States to obtain, produce, and disseminate foreign intelligence information.‚Äù 11Minimization procedures must also contain special limitations on the dissemination of U.S... person identities with respect to certain types of foreign intelligence information,212 as well as allow for the retention and dissemination of evidence of a crime to law enforcement entities.213 These statutory requirements obligate the Attorney General to adopt procedures that balance the at times competing interests in protecting the privacy of U.S. persons and the Intelligence Community‚Äôs production of foreign intelligence information to meet national security requirements. In addition, although the minimization procedures must be designed to protect U.S. persons‚Äô privacy, the procedures will at times provide controls on data that protect the privacy of non-U.S. persons as well."  'A Comprehensive Look at the FISC Order Legal Analysis' https://www.lawfareblog.com/comprehensive-look-fisc-order-legal-analysis  'Maintaining America‚Äôs Ability to Collect Foreign Intelligence: The Section 702 Program' https://www.lawfareblog.com/maintaining-americas-ability-collect-foreign-intelligence-section-702-program

text: I don't understand this, I really don't. The government isn't spying on naked women or reading people'e emails for fun. It's a matter of national security. If you honestly believe that we can apply the constitution that was written in the 1700s to the modern era, you're delusional. The government is here to protect it's citizens first and foremost. If they look through the world's emails to try and make sure there aren't any discussions on threats to the country, then I'm ok with them "reading" all of my emails. I have nothing to hide. The ONLY people that should be worried about this are the people who want to hurt the United States. To think that the government actually cares about what groceries you want your husband to pick up from the grocery list is stupid. This type of surveillance is necessary in such a technologically advanced era in order to protect the citizens from threats made on the country, and now that this information is public, people that DO want to hurt the US now know the ways around being found out. This is just my opinion though, and no I won't call you a dumbass for thinking differently.

text: Snowdon is not just a patriot to the US. He's a hero in many ways to the rest of the world. I'm a Brit and I find it insane that he could even be considered a traitor. What happened to that spirit that fought off the greatest empire in the history of the world?   I have no illusions about the harsh realities of the world, I believe that sometimes we need to do bad things to bad people so that good people can live a normal life.  But, there IS a line, that line, the fact that it exists is what we must always strive to keep, because when the ends don't just justify some means, but all means, we become unworthy of the freedoms our ancestors died for. By taking away our freedoms for security, we become what we despise. We become what our enemies believe us to be. They win.  Your founding father Benjamin Franklin said it best.  "Those who give up their liberty for more security neither deserve liberty nor security". text: I can‚Äôt wait for this film to come out, it will be interesting to see how they portray someone like Snowden. After watching the trailer, I decided to added a quick fact about the stud everyone knows as Snowden. On October 26 of 2004, located at Fort Bragg North Carolina, I found myself in a unit by the name of "The John F. Kennedy Special Warfare Training Center. Here I was in a specific training course named Special Forces Preparation Course Phase one. Here is where I witnessed Edward Snowden during our morning formation, walk out in front of about 50 soldiers, walk up onto a 3-foot-high platform, and with a wooden mallet he struck a copper colored gong (Big round saucer) signifying he quit the course. Edward Snowden was never seen again in any other special forces training courses that I can recall, to include never even going to the actual SFAS to actually begin the Special Forces Training. After Mr. Snowden Quite his butt when "Needs of the Army" like everyone else that signed a contract to go through the course. Where he went from that point on I can‚Äôt say, but I love Hollywood and the stretching of the truth and making someone seem cooler then what they really are. My personnel opinion from being around this man, he is a snake in the grass looking for the easy way out of everything (Don't trust him). And by the way, I also was in basic training with Snowden, and for the life of me I don‚Äôt recall him having broken legs, LOL Some people love the spot light and are willing to lie through their teeth to get it. Have a good one. Dave.

text: Edward Snowden and Chris Kyle. Two American heroes favored and hated by two different sides. One side calls Snowden a true hero that gave the American people vital and classified information which the government was knowingly hiding from them to protect their own interest while the other side calls him a traitor for doing just that. One side calls Kyle a true American hero for saving several lives of fellow soldiers during war, while the other side calls him a mass murderer for killing so many innocent Iraqi lives simply to protect his fellow soldiers on the battlefield. Even though both may have smeared or revered America's name in the world, they both didn't care what we people thought of them and did what they thought was the right thing to do. In Snowden's case, it's surprising to see just how many people might call him a "sell out" even though his courageous act gave people such knowledge they weren't even aware of, such as how their own government and tax dollars funded technology that in turn could spy on their own private lives.

That would cost them $4,800,000,000,000 (More than HALF of the US GDP) in server equipment alone! Also, that would require them to have a bandwidth of over 1 TB/S (about the equivalent of 8,000 gigabit connections, or about $10,000,000 a year in internet costs) , which is not possible.

text: We went and watched the new movie by Oliver Stone, "Snowden", this evening.  It's very good.  I saw the earlier documentary, "Citizen Four" by Laura Poitras, and Oliver Stone's movie doesn't diverge much from the earlier documentary, except in the sense that this is made to be dramatic.  I was on the edge of my seat for most of the movie.  It was gripping.  It brought home the horror of a huge clandestine organization, staffed by the most brilliant people in the world, working against the principles of liberty, justice and democracy.  Unlike most thrillers and espionage movies, this was about reality.    I didn't leave the theater feeling comfortable, but I left it feeling very grateful to Edward Snowden, Laura Poitras, Glen Greenwald, Oliver Stone, and all of those who worked to pull aside the curtain to reveal the inner workings of our Land of Oz.  It is a great comfort to think that this movie will be shown to millions of viewers across the world, and that people like Edward Snowden, Chelsea Manning and Julian Assange will not have made their sacrifices in vain.    I think that this is something that liberals and conservatives can agree upon:  A surveillance state that collects information to manipulate people, events, and governments, to consolidate its power and sovereignty across the globe, is not the America that we pledge allegiance to.

text: An asymmetric rule of law is the rule of tyrannical men.  The biggest problem in the defense of liberty today is moral decline. Immoral persons appear moral only when the law advances thier appetites' desire - An honorable measure of things is lost when man measures things with his person as the measure. Such a corrupt population will accept corrupt JUDGES, corrupt politicians, corrupt journalists, corrupt military, and corrupt police.  If we fix ourselves fixing our world becomes possible.  But the difficulty is that NOW we are some somewhere in transition.  This can be resolved by once again recognizing that for criminal culpability to attach to the violation of criminal law the act must have been performed with criminal intent - that is intent not driven by an actually higher law.  Under this Snowden's actions do not appear to warrant punishment under criminal law. Snowden's action would still make him civilly liable if his actions damaged the owners of the information by distributing it to others who were not rightful owners of the information.  It appears to me that the information was a public good in that it became more valuable the more widely it is possessed by individuals. If so then Snowden's publication of information created more value than it destroyed. =========================== Is the above the true balance of things regarding the complaints against Snowden? Our government has designed the system in way that's perfect for them: they've made us completely dependable on them,  especially on the entertainment front. They saturate our minds with so many distractions that at the end of the day we're more worried about movies and sports than about the government. They know very well that as long as they keep us well entertained, we'll behave ourselves, the way you put on a movie for a kid and he stays put. Putin does not want the CIA to know just what secrets Snowden had with him, even if those secrets were unimportant. Keeping the NSA and CIA guessing about that  is in Putin's favor. There is a long list of people that got in Putin's way that Putin has liquidated.
